english:
  title: Record of the Celestial Platform Law King Temple in the Great Capital
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the third year of Zhizheng, in the spring of the year guiwei, the Law King Temple was completed. Lord Zhao, Grand Commandant of Splendid Rank and Director of the Imperial Medical Academy, came to request that I write this record. He spoke thus:

    "I am a native of Yeongchun in Goryeo. Since the year guisi of the Zhiyuan era, I was selected to serve as an attendant in the imperial palace, where I have continued to this day. I humbly observe that Emperor Sejong wielded his divine might without taking life, and thus was able to unite all under heaven. Successive sages have inherited his way, bringing rest and nourishment to the people—all rooted in compassion and love. Therefore the Buddha's teaching of loving-kindness resonates mysteriously with this principle, which we honor and embrace. This moved my heart with reverence and longing. Yet reflecting further, though unworthy and humble, I have received undeserved imperial favor. Now that I grow old, I wish to repay this debt, yet find no means to do so. Thus I humbly follow the Buddha's teaching and establish this temple: above, to wish long life for the sovereign and pay respects to former emperors; below, to benefit all living beings eternally. Recording these matters, I entrust their lasting preservation to you."

    I reflect that the way of a minister is to devote oneself and exhaust one's strength in fulfilling what must be done. The earnest heart that wishes to bless one's lord cannot help but overflow; yet there are things beyond our power to accomplish. These we entrust to the Buddha. It is thus that this temple came to be.

    Considering the Buddha's teaching: it arose in the Eastern Han, yet the three kingdoms of Korea, lying where the sun rises, might have seemed distant from Western teachings. Yet observing now, throughout the mountains and streams, vestiges of the dharma appear in places that preceded even China. The people's customs in serving sovereigns and parents, in nurturing the living and honoring the dead, follow entirely the Buddha's way. Those who do otherwise face the bewilderment and censure of the multitude, accused of failing in loyalty and filial duty. Alas, customs long established have obscured their origins. Even now, beneath the imperial capital, temples bearing the name "Goguryeo" stand everywhere. How natural that the lord pursues this work.

    Before this, the Treasury Commissioner Li Samjin had converted his residence in Anbu Quarter into a Buddhist sanctuary, naming it the Law King Temple. He appointed the monk Jishin to oversee it. Later it became a stable for a powerful household, and Commissioner Li sought compensation to establish another site, yet could not succeed. Growing old and ill, he despaired—until hearing of the lord's undertaking, he entrusted it to him as patron. Day after day the lord appealed to Li's household and received half its value in paper currency: twenty-five thousand strings. Adding his own gift of fifteen thousand strings and seven thousand contributed by Director Shen of the Bureau of Precious Vessels, he purchased land in the Gold City Quarter and entrusted Jishin with its development.

    Shortly after, Commissioner Li passed away. The lord and his wife, Lady Cui, sold their clothing and vessels to gather further funds. First they built shelters on three sides for tenants; then they constructed a hall within to house the Buddha image. Jishin too eventually departed this life. In the second month of the year gengshen, they invited Master Yiyin of the Celestial Platform school to preside. They sculpted golden images of Shakyamuni, Manjushri, Samantabhadra, and the Celestial Platform master Zhizhe, thereby revealing the teaching of the three contemplations in one mind. When this became known, the Central Palace granted ten thousand sheets of paper currency to support the work. The following year they built east and west halls; then a southern gallery extending northward to connect with the main hall, providing quarters for the monks. They opened a corridor gate serving as the three-gate entrance, flanked the main hall with wings for receiving guests, then built a one-pace cottage behind the hall with chambers for attendants in its southeastern corner, along with kitchen and storerooms to the south. The total expenditure in paper currency exceeded one hundred and forty thousand strings, for more than eighty structures. Neither excessive in grandeur nor deficient in dignity, the images stand solemn and majestic, their gilding and azure gleaming brilliantly. Every ceremonial vessel and offering implement the temple should possess was provided without lack.

    That autumn, when the emperor resided in the Western Palace, someone presented the golden-character Lotus Sutra; the emperor commanded it be preserved in this temple. The Central Palace subsequently sent fragrant tribute to support its recitation. The following year this was repeated—thus honoring the sublime dharma while approving the lord's diligence in service to the throne.

    During the height of construction, Master Yiyin declared: "Our order relies upon the Buddha's grace and depends on others for sustenance—how could we withhold our donations?" He gave all the accumulated treasure of his alms bowl—five thousand strings. Commissioner Park Swa-no-ul-dae of the Directorate of Commoners and Craftsmen, and Minister Zhu Wan-ze Tiemuer of the Palace Directorate, each contributed two thousand strings toward the perpetual lamps. Good-hearted villagers pledged to gather contributions in spring and autumn, listening to the great sutras recited, making this an annual custom. Beginning in the year jiaxu and concluding in guiwei, ten years passed—a mere moment in the eyes of eternity.

    I have observed that building temples and pagodas is difficult, yet their destruction is easy. Though one provides grand dwellings and abundant food, later inhabitants treat such places as business for personal gain, and when profit exhausts itself, the temple perishes alongside it. Though people know this truth, they continue regardless, saying only: "I have given my heart, I have exhausted my strength—what comes after is not my concern." Do not merely speak thus. The lord, having completed this temple, causes its record to be carved in stone for a purpose. Those who dwell here in future ages should take this deeply to heart.

    The temple stands where the late Censor Guanyin-no once dwelt, on land measuring nine mu. When work began, they unexpectedly discovered beneath the old foundations a stone fragment bearing three characters: "Law King Temple." The lord, sensing the workings of ancient karma, took this as confirmation and bestowed the name accordingly.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three kingdoms of Korea' (三韓) refers to Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla in the Korean peninsula.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'year gengshen' and chronological references anchor this record to the Yuan dynasty period (1353 CE).
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Central Palace' (中宮) refers to the empress's residence, indicating imperial-level patronage of the temple.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three contemplations in one mind' (一心三觀) is a central Tiantai Buddhist teaching about perceiving reality through unified meditation.
  - key: ''
    value: The discovery of the stone with the temple's name is presented as a sign of karmic predestination, a common trope in Buddhist narratives.
